<div id="comment_64623195" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64623195" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64623195" name="comment_link_64623195" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23386193&amp;cid=64623195" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64623195)" >Re:</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64623195" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64623195); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~angel'o'sphere">angel'o'sphere</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~angel'o'sphere">( 80593 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64623195"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64623195"><p>What is fucking hard is: it is a floppy drive. Not an IDE or SCSI drive.</p><p>That means the ancient software doing the read and write is basically writing and trading the data bit by bit.</p><p>Yes, bit, not byte. Most of those drives, could not even store bytes. For some reason that I forgot, the maximum number of consecutive 1's was 5. So a stream if 8 bit bytes has to be broken up into a stream of 5 bit words. Perhaps it was begin of sector and end of sector markers.</p><p>The device controlling hardware was primitive. The<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64623195">

